I&#39;ve given some thought to your idea, which asks, of course, the most 
embarrassing question that sits in the middle of this group, like the 
proverbial elephant in the parlor:

Is anyone going to do anything about it?

Here&#39;s some random thoughts on the matter:

I&#39;d like to point out, your idea is not totally new, since Teddy 
Roosevelt also thought that English spelling was a &quot;damn mess&quot;, and 
tried to promote spellings such as &quot;nite&quot; and &quot;tuf.&quot;  But even a man 
as bullish and Presidential as he couldn&#39;t get these ideas off the 
ground.

The linguist Mario Pei has the opposite approach to yours, and 
thought that spelling reform should have a more blitzkreig approach. 
Yes, he said, there would be chaos, but, since the new generation of 
toddlers that started to learn to read under the revised system would 
have absolutely no trouble at all (learning being learning), the 
chaos would only last for a few years - maybe half a generation - 
instead of a century. He said the adults opposing reform (as if there 
was some organized lobby!) always approached the problem from their 
point of view, not that of a child.

One side effect to your proposition:  what gets written in the 
transition time is going to look like a real tossed salad, and will 
appear as nothing but illiterate spelling to most of the planet.  And 
there is no greater snob than a spelling snob.

Shaw himself was adamant that his system use no symbols that could be 
mistaken for old-fashioned Latin typography.  (Except note the &quot;O&quot; 
that couldn&#39;t be stopped!)  In his quaint, Victorian way, he was 
concerned that using regular letters might create some embarassing 
and even obscene letter combinations! (One of the few times Shaw was 
a product of his times.)

I&#39;d also like to point out that we Americans have been dragging our 
feet in adopting the metric system for over 100 years, and that 
reform seems almost a piece of cake compared with the inertia that 
would confront even the most rabid spelling reformer.

Some members of the Shavian group have no interest in reform, but see 
the alphabet as a practical way to to teach non-English speakers our 
tongue.  I know of a Cambodian fellow of 20 who, right now, is faced 
not only with learning to spell, but how to write Latin characters 
for the first time in his life.Talk about a learning curve!  Think 
how much easier it would be for him to start with a system that made 
sense, where the shapes were the sounds!  Then, maybe after a year, 
and speaking well, he could slowly transition into conventional 
orthography.

Still, if there ever was a time that spelling reform was practical, 
this would be it.  With computers able to transliterate any text in 
an instant, people could download the Sunday Times in any spelling 
they liked, and the cost to the Times of producing such alternative 
texts would be next to nothing!

Still, I admire your optimism.  All for now......



