&gt;few minutes before each of my classes start.  Also, I&#39;ve developed a
&gt;script quite similar to Readspel, in fact, based largely on it.  If
&gt;some don&#39;t know what that is, it&#39;s a system of writing English using
&gt;most of the letters of the Latin alphabet, but applying the rule
&gt;of &#39;one letter per sound.&#39;  I figure that a system like this would
&gt;ease the populous into spelling reform.  Thus, comes my question.
&gt;
&gt;Does anyone here actually plan on DOING anything to try to reform
&gt;spelling?  If so, how do you plan to go about it?  An approach I&#39;d
&gt;thought of, is to introduce it slowly and gradually.  For example,
&gt;differentiate between &#39;th&#39; in &quot;this&quot; and &#39;th&#39; in &quot;thing.&quot;  Then,
&gt;maybe make &#39;ng&#39; one letter.  And gradually, introduce a seperate
&gt;letter to write each of the consonant sounds that are usually written
&gt;with more than one (i.e. sh, ch, ng, th, dh).  Note that there would
&gt;be a small amount of time, a few months let&#39;s say, between each small
&gt;change, allowing the populous to grow accustomed to the changes. 
&gt;Then, as soon as the consonant sounds are all introduced as one
&gt;letter, leave that for a while, then introduce a single letter for
&gt;each of the vowel sounds.  I believe that it can actually BE DONE,
&gt;but that it would be much easier, and much more accepted, if it were
&gt;done slowly and gradually.  What do you think?
